{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487475"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:11:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:11:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"357"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/357"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.02,0.03,0.09,0.7]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"357"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92811"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/357"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"357"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76171"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"331"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2207"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"869"},{"type":"contributions","id":"871"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13984"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31837"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31839"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42066"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43793"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92811"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with several episodes of light-headedness, palpitations and sweating. These symptoms seem to occur within a few hours after a large meal. She has a medical history of hypertension, for which she takes metoprolol. She also has a history of cholecystectomy and total gastrectomy for carcinoma one year earlier. Until recently she was only managing small meals. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 100/min and regular, blood pressure 110/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. The rest of the examination is unremarkable. Her blood glucose level is 1.7 mmol/L (3.9-7.8).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Insulinoma","Adrenal insufficiency","Carcinoid tumour","Idiopathic reactive hypoglycaemia","Dumping syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classical picture of late \u003Cstrong\u003Edumping syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. Dumping syndrome is a potential complication of oesophagogastric or bariatric surgery, whereby undigested carbohydrate-rich gastric contents are delivered rapidly into the duodenum. This causes a biphasic reaction:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEarly dumping (within one hour post-prandial) - caused by osmotic fluid shifts from the intravascular space into the intestinal lumen, prompting a neurohumoral response to volume depletion and subsequent GI symptoms (pain, bloating, diarrhoea) with vasomotor features (palpitations, tachycardia, hypotension).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELate dumping (1-3 hours post-prandial) - caused by hyperinsulinaemia triggered by the larger than normal carbohydrate load, driving glucose into cells and thus causing hypoglycaemia. The resulting neuroglycopaenia manifests as dizziness, confusion, and fatigue, with overlaid adrenergic features of perspiration, palpitations, and tremor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDumping syndrome may occur in up to 80% of patients who have had a Roux-en-Y gastric bypass procedure. It occurs more frequently in association with large meals. In some patients, these symptoms may not occur until many months after the procedure, perhaps when they are starting to eat larger meals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare neuroendocrine tumour that secretes insulin. While it can cause hypoglycaemia, it typically does so independently of meals and would not explain the relationship to large meals or the history of gastric surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenal insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E can present with hypoglycaemia, fatigue, and postural hypotension. However, symptoms typically worsen during periods of stress rather than specifically after meals. Additionally, other features such as hyperpigmentation, hyponatraemia, and hyperkalaemia would be expected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoid tumour\u003C/strong\u003E can cause flushing and diarrhoea, but these symptoms are typically not related to meals in the way described. Furthermore, carcinoid syndrome is rare and usually associated with liver metastases, which are not mentioned in this patient\u0027s history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic reactive hypoglycaemia\u003C/strong\u003E refers to hypoglycaemia occurring after meals in individuals without diabetes, with the idiopathic form of this condition specifically occurring in patients without a clear anatomical cause such as gastric surgery. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to diagnosing dumping syndrome in this case is recognising the relationship between symptoms and large meals, the history of gastric surgery, and the presence of hypoglycaemia. Management typically involves dietary modifications, such as smaller, more frequent meals, and avoiding simple carbohydrates.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dumping syndrome is a common sequela to gastric surgery and resection, characterised by early and late symptoms related to rapid gastric emptying.","Late dumping syndrome typically presents 1-3 hours after meals with hypoglycaemia and associated symptoms of neuroglycopaenia and adrenergic response.","Management of dumping syndrome involves dietary modifications including smaller, more frequent meals and avoiding simple carbohydrates."],"references":["Berg P, McCallum R. Dumping Syndrome: A Review of the Current Concepts of Pathophysiology, Diagnosis, and Treatment. Dig Dis Sci 2016; 61:11-18. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26396002/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76171"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"357"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76171"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-19T13:58:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-19T15:32:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"357"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92811"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"}